                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 812.00/11553.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Chargé <persName type="from">O’Shaughnessy</persName> to the
                            <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">American Embassy</hi>, <lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Mexico City</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1914-04-19T19:00:00-06:36">
                            <hi rend="italic">April 19, 1914, 7 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>869. I called at the Foreign Office at 5:50 p.m. and the Minister for Foreign
                    Affairs handed me a note verbale which states in substance that the Mexican
                    Government is not disposed to accede to the unconditional demand of the
                    Government of the United States but it is disposed to act according to the terms
                    of the protocol which I have already transmitted to you. I told him actually
                    that so far as this Embassy is concerned the matter is closed and that I should
                    inform my Government that General Huerta had definitely refused the demands of
                    the United States. I am cabling a translation of note later.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Nelson O’Shaughnessy</hi>
                    </signed>.</closer>
            </div>
        </body>
